%S A393490 1,9,80,18503,798012,61059200,5945101515,540570246900,55009289706509,
%T A393490 6033063333399673,690255516954482251,82801796609079357660,
%U A393490 10355438037306564332825,1341657610987962263146348,179082413357385720860400743,24571014988510561366931242323
%N A393490 a(n) is the number of different ways in which three particles move from A->B, B->C, and C->A on an equilateral triangular grid ABC of side n units, starting simultaneously and moving at the same constant speed along the grid lines, such that the distance of each particle from its starting corner is always increasing, and no two particles ever meet.
%C A393490 Let ABC be an equilateral triangular grid of side n containing n^2 unit equilateral triangles. X axis is defined along AB and Y axis is defined along AC such that starting point A has coordinates (0,0), finishing point B has coordinates (n,0) and C is at (0,n).
%C A393490 A grid point (x,y) on a path of the moving point P satisfies the following conditions when generating string of coordinates of grid points on a valid path.
%C A393490 x + y <= n, y <= n/2 and x^2 + y^2 + x*y should increase when moving to the next grid point. As P moves from one grid point to the next x remains unchanged or increased by 1 unit. If x does not change y should increase by 1 unit, if x increases by 1 unit y should remain unchanged or decreased by 1 unit.
%C A393490 Each of P path from A to B gives a unique S path from B to C and R path from C to A by transforming a grid point (h, k) on P path into (n - h - k, h) on S path and into (k,n-h-k) on R path. Any two grid paths do not meet if r-th coordinate of one path is different from r-th coordinate of the other. The r-th and (r+1)-th coordinates of one grid path must not appear swapped in another at positions r and r+1. Paths do not need to have equal length.
%H A393490 Janaka Rodrigo, <a href="/A393490/a393490.txt">Python Code for distinct sets of triplets of grid paths</a>
%e A393490 n = 2 has 9 different ways to do this:
%e A393490 Grid paths from A to B:
%e A393490   P1:{(0,0), (1,0), (2,0)},
%e A393490   P2:{(0,0), (0,1), (1,1), (2,0)},
%e A393490   P3:{(0,0), (1,0), (1,1), (2,0)}.
%e A393490 Grid paths from B to C:
%e A393490   S1:{(2,0), (1,1), (0,2)},
%e A393490   S2:{(2,0), (1,0), (0,1), (0,2)},
%e A393490   S3:{(2,0), (1,1), (0,1), (0,2)}.
%e A393490 Grid paths from C to A:
%e A393490   R1:{(0,2), (0,1), (0,0)},
%e A393490   R2:{(0,2), (1,1), (1,0), (0,0)},
%e A393490   R3:{(0,2), (0,1), (1,0), (0,0)}.
%e A393490 Set of valid triplets of grid paths:
%e A393490   {(P2,R2,S2), (P3,R2,S3), (P3,R3,S1), (P3,R1,S3), (P3,R1,S1), (P1,R3,S3), (P1,R3,S1), (P1,R1,S3), (P1,R1,S1)}.
%e A393490 Therefore a(2) = 9.
%Y A393490 Cf. A393796, A394097, A394098, A357603.
